description: While birding along Omaruru riverbed (dry), found a watering hole that was likely an abandoned well dug by a long-gone farmer. Bulrushes were growing in the small pond, and at least 3 species of dragonfly were actively flitting around. There were 2 of this large "Black Emperor Dragonfly" laying eggs.  Location is accurate, as eBird tracked our walking route.
Markings and color are quite different from Anax Imperator

description: The female. Very large. I flew over the lamp in the Merlot Park restaurant. Visually, yellow markings on the abdomen were visible, but through the bright light it was not possible to make better shots. Apart from A. tristis, as far as I understand, there are no other Aeshnidae with a green head and chest and a black and yellow belly in this area.
Final photo shows scale of dragonfly alongside a standard 86x54mm credit card.
